    {
      "id": "e9d9ae8fa0f9eed4bb8e627de6d7d5a572f28e03",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 377,
        "name": "wc-checkpatch",
        "username": "hpdd-checkpatch",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2015-02-10 16:16:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nLooks good to me.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "055510675d7044e417dfd9824ae029ef80c8fabc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-11 10:34:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI guess the problem with the timestamps at layout swap is not the timestamps in the MDS inode, but rather the timestamps in the OST objects, which are newly updated during the restore.  Even if the atime/mtime are reset to the original times via futimes() the ctime will not be reset, hence John's FUTIMES_3 ioctl.  The unpleasant thing about that is it exposes the ability to reset ctime to userspace, which isn't normally possible.\n\nHowever, instead of having the MDS do this on behalf of the client, it seems possible to have the client calling the LL_IOC_HSM_COPY_END ioctl copy or zero the timestamps on the OST objects internally using ll_setattr_raw() without exposing it to userspace.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c7cd6767b339cf50d1b25087694a5048bac6b6af",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2015-05-04 14:45:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> The unpleasant thing about that is it exposes the ability to reset ctime to userspace, which isn't normally possible.\n\nGranted, but we do require CAP_SYS_ADMIN.\n\n> However, instead of having the MDS do this on behalf of the client, it seems possible to have the client calling the LL_IOC_HSM_COPY_END ioctl copy or zero the timestamps on the OST objects internally using ll_setattr_raw() without exposing it to userspace.\n\nI think it's better if we compose the overall functionality from several smaller system calls rather than have one big and complicated ioctl.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
